2026-04-16 12:13:16 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['Internal series diode in load module'] hypothesis_explanation='From all tests, the system polarity from the PSU through the control module to the load module is consistently inverted at about −12 V relative to the PSU negative, yet all cabling and module internal wirings (PSU rails, control indicator LED orientation, control‑to‑load continuity) have been verified as correct and not faulty. The red LED in the control module is ON, confirming that its internal rails see the incoming polarity as reversed with respect to the PSU. The only remaining element that controls whether current can reach the lamp in this reversed‑polarity situation is the series diode in the load module. The measurement shows its anode at approximately −12 V and its cathode near 0 V, meaning it is reverse‑biased for the actual PSU polarity reaching the load. In nominal operation, the diode must be oriented so it is forward‑biased when the cables are correctly connected (+ at the diode anode, 0 V at the cathode). Given that the external cabling has been proven correct and all other polarity suspects have been ruled out by repair attempts, the most plausible root cause is that the series diode itself is installed backwards (or otherwise internally miswired) in the load module. This prevents any current from ever reaching the lamp or the internal lamp indicator, so the lamp stays off despite the rest of the circuit being powered and the red LED indicating the polarity anomaly upstream.'
